  "shortBio": "Dawnkits are radiant-touched Riftlings of Radiant Citadel, four-footed and sure on uneven ground. Often mistaken for simple radiant beasts, they are social companions known for halo edge instincts and a quiet talent for reading unstable air. In Radiant Citadel, they favor Radiant Lily and soft routines.",
  "standardBio": "Dawnkit, titled among keepers as “Dawnshaft Companion,” carries hopeful duty in every movement. Native to Radiant Citadel, the species clarifies through sunshaft and pale gold, leaving traces that other Riftlings can follow like soft maps. Wild groups form loose bonds rather than rigid packs; a social individual may become the emotional center of a small hearthline. They eat Radiant Lily eagerly and dislike food that smells of neglect or spoilage. Ancient keepers carved Dawnkit silhouettes into travel stones, believing the species guided the lost. Modern hatcheries record them as reliable companions; their emotional intelligence above tool craft makes training feel like conversation. Their signature ability, Dawnkit's Aura Slash, reflects a life shaped by Radiant Citadel more than by arena ambition. Many assume Dawnkits are aggressive because of their radiant affinity; most are cautious first. Young Dawnkits practice Dawnkit's Aura Slash as play long before they understand battle. Adults teach by demonstration: where to rest, what to avoid, how to share warmth or shade.",
  "fullLore": "Dawnkits first condensed from residual prismdawn along the living edges of Radiant Citadel after early Rift fractures cooled into weather. Their eggs appear where sunshaft and pale gold gathers into stillness—never in the loudest danger, always in the pocket of calm beside it. Early surveyors mistook them for ambient phenomena until a Dawnkit returned a dropped lantern, carefully, as if returning a promise.\n\nIn ancient eras, regional peoples treated Dawnkits as omen-bearers rather than pets. Carvings show them walking ahead of caravans, pausing at unstable ground, and curling around children during ashfall or fog. The species was never “tamed” in the old sense; it chose. That choice culture survives in modern Riftkeeper etiquette: you do not yank a Dawnkit into a bond. You invite, wait, and keep the invitation honest.\n\nModern history is quieter and more practical. Hatcheries map Dawnkit care cycles with the same seriousness given to rare lines, because common does not mean shallow. Radiant Citadel still holds wild populations that trade soft greetings with passerby pets. After major Rift events, Dawnkits often appear first at recovery centers—not as heroes, but as inventory clerks of comfort, counting who is cold, hungry, or afraid.\n\nNatural behavior is social at the core and adaptable at the edges. They are four-footed and sure on uneven ground, companion-sized, easy to cradle, and communicate through body posture and scent marks. Socially, they prefer small trusted circles; strangers are assessed by scent, posture, and whether a keeper’s voice stays kind under stress. Intelligence presents as emotional intelligence above tool craft. They sleep in shallow scrapes and prefer weather that matches their affinity’s comfort band.\n\nEcologically, Dawnkits act as seed dispersers of calm within Radiant Citadel. Allies often include Celestora and Lightspire; rivalries with Stonegrub and Lightspire are usually about nesting space or shiny refuse, not blood feuds. Predators are rare—most threats come from collapsing terrain and careless machines rather than jaws.\n\nCulture around them is affectionate and slightly superstitious. Festival stories say the first Riftkeepers learned patience by watching Dawnkits wait out weather rather than fight it. Collectors prize unusual cosmetics, yet marketplace notes remind buyers that verified care history matters more than glitter. The common misunderstanding remains: Many assume Dawnkits are aggressive because of their radiant affinity; most are cautious first. The hidden truth keepers debate in soft rooms is simpler and stranger: Their sunshaft and pale gold scent intensifies near forgotten vaults, which may explain keeper superstitions.\n\nFrom egg to evolved form, their life story stays continuous. Eggs look like glazed stones veined with radiant light. Hatchlings are clumsy with sincerity; adults become specialists of place; evolved stages sharpen instinct without erasing childhood habits. Battle tendencies favor protective bursts, and evolution philosophy insists transformation should answer lived experience—not fashion.\n\nFor Riftkeepers, a Dawnkit is a living chapter of Radiant Citadel. Feed it Radiant Lily, respect its social tempo, and it will teach you the region’s quieter grammar: which winds lie, which stones remember, which silences are safe. Personal quests often begin with a shell symbol, a remembered scent, or a dream of a door that only opens when the bond is honest. That is the Dawnkit bargain—not destiny sold at rarity price, but a life that continues because you showed up.",
